('PLD 2015 Supreme Court 6', 'All Pakistan Legal Decisions ', 'Ghulam Rasool v. Government of Pakistan through Secretary, Establishment Division Islamabad and others', 'Supreme Court Pakistan', 'Chief Justice Nasir ul Mulk, Juatice Amir Hani Muslim, Justice Ahmed Chaudhry', '2014-10-30', ' Abdul Rahim Bhatti | Khurram Mumtaz Hashmi        ', '', 'Section 2(b) of the Civil Servants Act 1973, Companies Ordinance 1984, Article 90 of the Constitution of Pakistan 1973, Article 184(3) of the Constitution of Pakistan, 199 of the Constitution of Pakistan, Public Service Act 1999, Federal Accountability Act 2006, maintainability, constitutional petition, civil servants, matter for Federal Service Tribunal, appointment for constitutional posts, administrative issues, schedule of posts, power of appointment, high-level appointments, powers of vetting, suitable candidates, specific appointments, public appointments, merit-based selections, Public Appointment Assessors, unfair appointment process, care-taker Government, recruitment process, judicial review', 'Civil Servants Act 1973, Section 2(b)|Constitution of the Islamic Republic of Pakistan 1973, Article 9, Article 90, Article 184(3)|Federal Public Service Commission of Pakistan Ordinance 1977|Companies Ordinance 1984|NEPRA Act 1997|Pakistan Telecommunication (Re-organization) Act 1997 \r\nPublic Service Act 1999| Pakistan Electronic Media Regulatory Authority Ordinance 2002|Oil and Gas Regulatory Authority Ordinance 2002|Federal Accountability Act 2006|Competition Act 2010 ', '\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nStereo. H C J D A 38.\r\n\r\n  \r\n\r\nJudgment Sheet\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nIN THE LAHORE HIGH COURT AT LAHORE\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nJUDICIAL DEPARTMENT\r\n\r\n  \r\n\r\nI.C.A No. 918 of 2010\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nJUDGMENT\r\n\r\n  \r\n\r\nDate of Hearing      01.10.2014\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nAppellant by           Mr.Hasham Ahmad Khan, Advocate. Respondent by        Ch. Muhammad Khalid Dogar, Advocate.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nMr.Waqas  Qadeer  Dar,  Deputy  Attorney\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nGeneral.\r\n\r\n   \r\n\r\nIjaz ul Ahsan, J:  The appellant is aggrieved of an order\r\n\r\n  \r\n\r\ndated  20.10.2010  passed  by  a  learned  Single  Bench  of  this Court. Through the impugned order a constitutional  petition filed by respondent No.1 was allowed and a demand of Rs.19,000/- as service and warranty charges made by the appellant  and  respondent  No.4  was  declared  to  have  been created without lawful authority and of no legal effect.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n2.       Facts  of  the  case  are  that  respondent  No.1  booked  a tractor through respondent No.4 by availing a loan facility from Zarai Taraqiati Bank Limited, Pasroor. The appellant asked respondent No.1 to present a demand draft for delivery of the tractor and the same was presented. Subsequently, a further amount of Rs.19,000/- was demanded as service and warranty charges which was challenged before this Court through a constitutional petition.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n3.     It appears that the actual price of the tractor was Rs.3,20,000/-  and  the  demand  of  Rs.19,000/-  was  over  and above the said price by way of service and warranty charges.INSERT INTO `caselaw` (`citation`, `journaltitle`, `title`, `court`, `bench`, `date`, `lawyers`, `areaoflaw`, `keywords`, `sourcescited`, `text`, `casescited`) VALUES
